  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"A True Story\", \"Based On A True Story\" and \"Inspired By A True Story\" in movies?",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of the differences:\n\n\"A True Story\":\n- Indicates the film depicts events very closely to actual historical facts\n- Most faithful to the original events\n- Minimal artistic liberalization\n- Highest level of claimed authenticity\n\n\"Based On A True Story\":\n- Follows the core narrative of real events\n- Some details might be changed or dramatized\n- Major plot points remain generally accurate\n- Moderate level of artistic interpretation\n- More creative liberty than \"A True Story\"\n\n\"Inspired By A True Story\":\n- Loosely connected to real events\n- Significant creative and dramatic modifications\n- Only basic premise or few details might be true\n- Lowest level of claimed historical accuracy\n- Primarily a fictional narrative with minimal real-world connection\n\nExample:\n- \"A True Story\": A documentary-like approach\n- \"Based On A True Story\": A film like \"Spotlight\" about the Boston Globe investigation\n- \"Inspired By A True Story\": A movie like \"Titanic\", which uses a real historical event as a backdrop for a fictional love story\n\nThe phrases are essentially a spectrum of authenticity, with increasing levels of artistic interpretation and creative freedom.",
